SIMPLE: easterling
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Easterling
<hw>East"er*ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Sterling</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native of a country
eastward of another; -- used, by the English, of traders or others from
the coasts of the Baltic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Merchants of Norway, Denmark, . . . called . . .
<qex>Easterlings</qex> because they lie east in respect of us.</q>
<rj><qau>Holinshed.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A piece of money coined in the east by
<person>Richard II.</person> of England.</def>
<rj><au>Crabb.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld> <def>The smew.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Easterling</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Easterling
<hw>East"er*ling</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Relating to the money of the
Easterlings, or Baltic traders. See <er>Sterling</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Easterly</ent>⟦br⟧
